n Island (The Philippines) -- t11 Ecologism as an Idiom in Amazonian Anthropology -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnthropologists know that conservation often disempowers already under-privileged groups, and that it also fails to protect environments. Through a series of ethnographic studies, this book argues that the real problem is not the disappearance of "pristine nature" or even the land-use practices of uneducated people. Rather, what we know about culturally determined patterns of consumption, production and unequal distribution, suggests that critical attention would be better turned on discourses of "primitiveness" and "pristine nature" so prevalent within conservation ideology, and on the historically formed power and exchange relationships that they help perpetuate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aConservation of natural resourcesxEconomic aspects. 0aConsumption (Economics)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aDistribution (Economic theory)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aDistributive justice. 0aEnvironmental ethics. 0aHuman ecologyxEconomic aspects. 0aMaterial accountability. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, David G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerglund, Eeva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerglund, Eeva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChatty, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllis, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/